Application on Trees
Scenario

A university stores student records in a hierarchical structure based on roll numbers. To efficiently search, insert, and delete student data, the system uses a Binary Search Tree (BST). Each node represents a student record, and the tree structure ensures quick access to data.

Justification

Tree data structures, especially Binary Search Trees, are useful when data needs to be maintained in a sorted manner. They allow efficient searching, insertion, and deletion compared to linear structures like arrays or linked lists. This is important in real-world systems such as databases, file systems, and hierarchical data storage.

Algorithm (BST Operations)

Insertion:

Start from the root.
If the tree is empty, create a new node as root.
If the value is less than the current node, move to the left child.
If the value is greater than the current node, move to the right child.
Repeat until the correct position is found and insert the node.

Search:

Start from the root.
If the value matches, return found.
If the value is smaller, search in the left subtree.
If larger, search in the right subtree.
Repeat until found or node becomes NULL.

Inorder Traversal:

Traverse left subtree.
Visit root.
Traverse right subtree.
Time Complexity
Insertion: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case
Search: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case
Traversal: O(n)
C Code (Without Comments)
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* left;
    struct Node* right;
};

struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->left = NULL;
    newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

struct Node* insert(struct Node* root, int data) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return createNode(data);
    if (data < root->data)
        root->left = insert(root->left, data);
    else if (data > root->data)
        root->right = insert(root->right, data);
    return root;
}

void inorder(struct Node* root) {
    if (root != NULL) {
        inorder(root->left);
        printf("%d ", root->data);
        inorder(root->right);
    }
}

int search(struct Node* root, int key) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return 0;
    if (root->data == key)
        return 1;
    if (key < root->data)
        return search(root->left, key);
    else
        return search(root->right, key);
}

int main() {
    struct Node* root = NULL;
    root = insert(root, 50);
    insert(root, 30);
    insert(root, 70);
    insert(root, 20);
    insert(root, 40);
    insert(root, 60);
    insert(root, 80);

    inorder(root);

    int key = 40;
    if (search(root, key))
        printf("\nFound");
    else
        printf("\nNot Found");

    return 0;
}
